---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CTA from '../components/CTA.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Why Perspectiv"
  description="Why Perspectiv exists, who we built it for, and how it's different from legacy enterprise monitoring suites."
>
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-50 to-white py-20 sm:py-24">
    <div class="container-prose text-center">
      <p class="section-eyebrow">Why Perspectiv</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-5xl">
        Built for IT teams that want less, sooner
      </h1>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg text-slate-600">
        Perspectiv exists because the gap between "enterprise monitoring suite"
        and "I just want to know if my network is up" got too wide. We built
        the tool we wanted as operators.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-white py-16">
    <div class="container-prose space-y-12">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900">
          Who this is for
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
          IT teams of 1–20 operators monitoring 50–2,000 devices across one
          or a few sites. Network engineers who'd rather spend an afternoon
          installing a tool than a quarter negotiating module licenses. Ops
          teams burned by per-node billing that turned a small network
          expansion into a budget meeting.
        </p>

        <figure class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
          <img
            src="/images/feature-device-manager.png"
            alt="Perspectiv device inventory showing a list of network devices with status indicators, vendor names, IP addresses, and uptime."
            class="block h-auto w-full"
            loading="lazy"
            decoding="async"
          />
          <figcaption class="border-t border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500">
            Device inventory page — vendor-detected, real-time status, ready for an SMB IT team's first install.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900">
          What we don't do
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
          <li>
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900">No tier gating on features.</span>{' '}
            Every capability ships in every plan. Tier difference is device
            cap, not unlocked modules.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900">No per-node billing.</span>{' '}
            Add devices, ICMP-monitor your whole subnet, run discovery sweeps
            — your bill doesn't move.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900">No mandatory cloud dependency.</span>{' '}
            Self-hosted by default. Your traffic flow data, your config
            backups, your SNMP creds — all stay on your hardware.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900">No multi-day install.</span>{' '}
            Docker Compose, two commands, you're at the bootstrap admin
            page in 10 minutes. No Windows server, no SQL Server license.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-500">
          A real story
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
          A typical SolarWinds deployment we've observed: 200–300 devices
          monitored, a database server with 160+ GB of RAM, requiring
          periodic reboots when the database "got clogged." And forced
          onto a 500-node tier license — not because the fleet was that
          big, but because key features the customer actually needed
          were gated behind it. Paying for capacity they'd never use.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
          The same workload runs on Perspectiv's <strong>Professional</strong>
          tier with <strong>16 GB of RAM</strong> — about 10× less hardware,
          no DB-clogging reboots, and no "you'll need to upgrade to access
          that" conversations. Every feature ships in every tier. Pick the
          tier that matches your fleet size, not the one that unlocks the
          module you need.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900">
          What we do well
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
          The standard SMB-network-engineer feature set, done thoroughly:
          SNMP polling with vendor-specific templates, NetFlow analysis,
          syslog and trap ingestion, configuration backup with diff history,
          IPAM, topology mapping via LLDP/CDP, agent-based server monitoring
          for Windows and Linux, multi-channel alerting with proper
          deduplication, custom dashboards, scheduled reports, full audit
          log, SSO integration, role-based access control. Built into one
          installable platform, not stitched together from add-on modules.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <figure class="overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
            <img
              src="/images/feature-device-details.png"
              alt="Perspectiv device detail page showing interface metrics, environment sensors, ARP table, and routing information."
              class="block h-auto w-full"
              loading="lazy"
              decoding="async"
            />
            <figcaption class="border-t border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500">
              Device detail — every metric SNMP exposes, in one page
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <figure class="overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
            <img
              src="/images/feature-netflow.png"
              alt="Perspectiv NetFlow analysis page showing top talkers, conversation flows, and application breakdown."
              class="block h-auto w-full"
              loading="lazy"
              decoding="async"
            />
            <figcaption class="border-t border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500">
              NetFlow — top talkers, conversations, applications
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <figure class="overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-slate-200 shadow-sm sm:col-span-2">
            <img
              src="/images/feature-reports.png"
              alt="Perspectiv reports page showing pre-built availability and performance reports with charts and summary tables."
              class="block h-auto w-full"
              loading="lazy"
              decoding="async"
            />
            <figcaption class="border-t border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500">
              Reports — pre-built availability, performance, lifecycle, scheduled to email
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900">
          Where we're going
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
          We ship roughly every other week. Charter customers (anyone in
          our pre-launch design partner program — see{' '}
          <a href="/charter">Charter</a>) get a direct line to influence
          the roadmap. The current focus areas are: deeper anomaly detection
          on time-series data, expanded vendor templates for SD-WAN and
          firewall platforms, and a SaaS-tier multi-tenant offering for MSPs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTA />
</BaseLayout>
